It's the reason you have
Santa Clara County Animal Care

00:51:29.750 --> 00:51:32.640
and Control spending
millions of dollars,

00:51:32.640 --> 00:51:34.994
why you have private
humane organizations caring

00:51:34.994 --> 00:51:35.910
for all these animals.

00:51:35.910 --> 00:51:39.310
If you add up the cost, it's
a couple of billion dollars

00:51:39.310 --> 00:51:41.140
a year in our society.

00:51:41.140 --> 00:51:44.400
But right now, we treat
everyone with, essentially,

00:51:44.400 --> 00:51:47.660
no tax on this behavior.

00:51:47.660 --> 00:51:53.460
There have been attempts
to have a fee for breeding.

00:51:53.460 --> 00:51:54.420
But it's been resisted.

00:51:54.420 --> 00:51:57.740
There's still, in our
country, this great tension

00:51:57.740 --> 00:52:00.630
we have between
liberty and justice.

00:52:00.630 --> 00:52:06.329
And I think that there are
folks who say, I'm responsible.

00:52:06.329 --> 00:52:07.120
I'm doing it right.

00:52:07.120 --> 00:52:08.650
I shouldn't be penalized.

00:52:08.650 --> 00:52:11.750
And that has been
a difficult thing

00:52:11.750 --> 00:52:14.770
to overcome in
state legislatures.

00:52:14.770 --> 00:52:17.280
I think what we're
trying to do is normalize

00:52:17.280 --> 00:52:20.730
the discussion about spaying and
neutering, and about adoption.

00:52:20.730 --> 00:52:23.360
And we're trying to attack,
with our Shelter Pet Project

00:52:23.360 --> 00:52:26.090
advertising campaign, which
is a national advertising

00:52:26.090 --> 00:52:30.700
campaign, the stigma associated
with animal shelter animals--

00:52:30.700 --> 00:52:32.220
that they're not
problem animals.

00:52:32.220 --> 00:52:33.930
It's usually a
human problem that

00:52:33.930 --> 00:52:36.260
resulted in the animal
being relinquished.

00:52:36.260 --> 00:52:37.520
Someone got divorced.

00:52:37.520 --> 00:52:38.140
They moved.

00:52:38.140 --> 00:52:40.390
They went to an apartment
that wouldn't allow animals.

00:52:40.390 --> 00:52:44.140
It's not the animal's fault.
The animal's not defective.

00:52:44.140 --> 00:52:47.550
So there's this notion somehow
that, while the breeder's

00:52:47.550 --> 00:52:50.527
animals are better, get one
of these puppy mill dogs,

00:52:50.527 --> 00:52:52.360
as we do all the time,
because we raid them.

00:52:52.360 --> 00:52:53.190
They're sick.

00:52:53.190 --> 00:52:54.140
They're inbred.

00:52:54.140 --> 00:52:55.510
There are all sorts of problems.

00:52:55.510 --> 00:52:58.760
The mixed breed animals are
actually much healthier,

00:52:58.760 --> 00:53:02.220
because they have a much
richer genetic diversity.

00:53:02.220 --> 00:53:05.730
And it means they've got
fewer of these chronic

00:53:05.730 --> 00:53:09.120
and hereditary
problems that plague

00:53:09.120 --> 00:53:10.520
certain breeds like bulldogs.

00:53:10.520 --> 00:53:11.770
They have this pushed-in face.

00:53:11.770 --> 00:53:13.390
They can't breathe very well.

00:53:13.390 --> 00:53:15.310
Dachshunds have
this elongated back.

00:53:15.310 --> 00:53:16.520
And they have back trouble.

00:53:16.520 --> 00:53:18.990
German shepherds
have hip problems.

00:53:18.990 --> 00:53:21.820
Almost all the breeds have
a laundry list of problems.

00:53:21.820 --> 00:53:24.310
So when you get more diversity,
and you mix the breeds,

00:53:24.310 --> 00:53:26.340
they have many fewer
health problems.

00:53:26.340 --> 00:53:29.390
Some of the large breed dogs
that can't live past seven

00:53:29.390 --> 00:53:34.890
or eight years-- I mean,
these are our creations

00:53:34.890 --> 00:53:36.180
of selective breeding.

00:53:36.180 --> 00:53:38.530
And there are lots
of physical problems

00:53:38.530 --> 00:53:41.100
that are borne by the
consumer in terms of higher

00:53:41.100 --> 00:53:43.640
veterinary cost, as well
as the emotional pain

00:53:43.640 --> 00:53:46.999
of having to see your animal
suffering or dying prematurely.

00:53:46.999 --> 00:53:48.790
AUDIENCE: It more has
to do with marketing.

00:53:48.790 --> 00:53:52.850
I found out that you're
right, but a lot of people

00:53:52.850 --> 00:53:54.600
still want a purebred.

00:53:54.600 --> 00:53:57.870
So what I found out is
that people are not aware

00:53:57.870 --> 00:54:00.190
that you can get a
purebred in rescue.

00:54:00.190 --> 00:54:02.320
And there's many,
many purebred rescues.

00:54:02.320 --> 00:54:05.385
And they have this notion
that all dogs in rescue

00:54:05.385 --> 00:54:09.040
are mixed dogs, it's mainly
pit bulls, and so on.

00:54:09.040 --> 00:54:11.775
And they never go to
even-- they don't know.

00:54:11.775 --> 00:54:12.650
They just don't know.

00:54:12.650 --> 00:54:14.960
They go and pay $2,000
for a purebred dog,

00:54:14.960 --> 00:54:18.040
and they don't know they could
have got one from a rescue.

00:54:18.040 --> 00:54:20.540
WAYNE PACELLE: That's one of
the many reasons why I want you

00:54:20.540 --> 00:54:21.920
to read my new book coming out.

00:54:21.920 --> 00:54:25.240
Because petfinder.com is part
of this humane revolution.

00:54:25.240 --> 00:54:28.830
Petfinder.com loads
pictures and information

00:54:28.830 --> 00:54:32.200
about available dogs and
cats, homeless dogs and cats.

00:54:32.200 --> 00:54:33.700
You can get any
kind of dog that you

00:54:33.700 --> 00:54:35.150
want by searching the website.

00:54:35.150 --> 00:54:37.250
If you go to a physical
brick and mortar shelter,

00:54:37.250 --> 00:54:38.791
you may not find
the animal you want,

00:54:38.791 --> 00:54:42.840
even though one third of them
are purebreds in shelters.

00:54:42.840 --> 00:54:43.900
But now you can find one.

00:54:43.900 --> 00:54:46.394
President Obama wanted
a Portuguese water dog.

00:54:46.394 --> 00:54:48.810
He could've gone on petfinder
and found a Portuguese water

00:54:48.810 --> 00:54:48.930
dog.

00:54:48.930 --> 00:54:50.346
You don't need to
go to a breeder.

00:54:50.346 --> 00:54:54.540
You can get any kind of dog that
you want through this channel.

00:54:54.540 --> 00:54:56.500
So you're right.

00:54:56.500 --> 00:54:58.000
AUDIENCE: Speaking
of pit bulls, I'm

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:00.860
wondering if you could
speak to any work that's

00:55:00.860 --> 00:55:05.120
being done about changing their
very unfortunate and undeserved

00:55:05.120 --> 00:55:06.955
reputation in shelters?

00:55:06.955 --> 00:55:09.010
WAYNE PACELLE:
Yeah, well, pitbulls

00:55:09.010 --> 00:55:11.060
are really not even a breed.

00:55:11.060 --> 00:55:12.784
We call them pit bull-type dogs.

00:55:12.784 --> 00:55:15.200
There are different kinds of
dogs-- American Staffordshire

00:55:15.200 --> 00:55:16.320
terrier and others.

00:55:16.320 --> 00:55:23.460
And they definitely have
been the victims of stigma.

00:55:23.460 --> 00:55:26.930
If you look back
historically in our culture,

00:55:26.930 --> 00:55:28.790
there were different
dogs who were

00:55:28.790 --> 00:55:32.650
viewed as the most menacing
and aggressive over time.

00:55:32.650 --> 00:55:35.510
In the post-slavery
era, bloodhounds

00:55:35.510 --> 00:55:38.100
were viewed as the
most vicious dogs.

00:55:38.100 --> 00:55:41.620
You can see pictures of
them, and their depictions

00:55:41.620 --> 00:55:44.360
in popular culture and in art.

00:55:44.360 --> 00:55:45.990
They were the vicious ones.

00:55:45.990 --> 00:55:49.900
They were chasing slaves,
and trying to get them back.

00:55:49.900 --> 00:55:54.050
When I was a kid, it
was Doberman Pinschers.

00:55:54.050 --> 00:55:57.400
There was also, before that,
it was German shepherds.

00:55:57.400 --> 00:56:00.540
There was a real craze with
Rottweilers for awhile.

00:56:00.540 --> 00:56:02.440
So pit bulls have
been kind of dominant

00:56:02.440 --> 00:56:06.410
as the badass dog for
the last 20 or 25 years.

00:56:06.410 --> 00:56:09.660
And some of it-- I went
to a fascinating lecture

00:56:09.660 --> 00:56:13.750
from a guy who works with
the Canine Research Center.

00:56:13.750 --> 00:56:17.920
And you can see these
popular media caricatures

00:56:17.920 --> 00:56:20.520
of the dogs that
have really driven

00:56:20.520 --> 00:56:23.140
this phony impression of them.

00:56:23.140 --> 00:56:27.370
And I don't know if any of you
remember the "Little Rascals,"

00:56:27.370 --> 00:56:30.270
but Petey, the dog, was
a pit bull-type dog.

00:56:30.270 --> 00:56:34.070
They were the great
American dog at one point.

00:56:34.070 --> 00:56:38.020
There is a circumstance
where some people, who

00:56:38.020 --> 00:56:41.680
are not well-behaved
themselves, get these dogs.

00:56:41.680 --> 00:56:44.380
And then they color the
behavior of the dogs.

00:56:44.380 --> 00:56:47.750
And it's because of
that sort of morphing

00:56:47.750 --> 00:56:51.060
of the dog based
on human behavior

00:56:51.060 --> 00:56:52.960
that this reputation develops.

00:56:52.960 --> 00:56:57.560
They are the most commonly
used dogs in fighting rings.

00:56:57.560 --> 00:57:00.230
But they were specifically
bred and trained

00:57:00.230 --> 00:57:02.340
not to attack the
people, because they're

00:57:02.340 --> 00:57:04.800
in with their handlers
when they're fighting.

00:57:04.800 --> 00:57:10.740
And they were bred and
trained to attack other dogs,

00:57:10.740 --> 00:57:12.150
but not to attack people.

00:57:12.150 --> 00:57:14.840
So there are lots of
convoluted parts of this.

00:57:14.840 --> 00:57:18.100
The chairman of our board
is a big pit bull enthusiast

00:57:18.100 --> 00:57:21.230
and he sleeps with three
in his bed every night.

00:57:21.230 --> 00:57:23.850
And we have a dogs in the office
policy at the Humane Society.

00:57:23.850 --> 00:57:26.720
I know you do at Google, as
well, which is fantastic.

00:57:26.720 --> 00:57:29.210
We wrote a book about
there's dogs in the office,

00:57:29.210 --> 00:57:31.950
and invoked Google's own policy.

00:57:31.950 --> 00:57:33.760
And the dogs are
so well behaved.

00:57:33.760 --> 00:57:38.070
And it's just a question
of properly raising them.

00:57:38.070 --> 00:57:40.310
AUDIENCE: I wanted to
ask you specifically

00:57:40.310 --> 00:57:44.380
about an issue happening right
now around the New York Blood

00:57:44.380 --> 00:57:45.610
Center.

00:57:45.610 --> 00:57:47.970
I know you wrote a letter
to the New York Blood Center

00:57:47.970 --> 00:57:49.560
a few months ago.

00:57:49.560 --> 00:57:52.850
And for those of
you who don't know,

00:57:52.850 --> 00:57:56.190
maybe you can speak to it
more eloquently than I.

00:57:56.190 --> 00:58:00.200
But there was a chimpanzee
colony in Liberia

00:58:00.200 --> 00:58:02.040
that's been used for
biomedical research

00:58:02.040 --> 00:58:04.840
by the New York Blood
Center for decades.

00:58:04.840 --> 00:58:08.680
And New York Blood Center has
recently essentially abandoned

00:58:08.680 --> 00:58:13.090
them, and ceased all
funding for their care.

00:58:13.090 --> 00:58:16.200
So the specific
question I have is,

00:58:16.200 --> 00:58:21.410
what can people like
myself do to encourage

00:58:21.410 --> 00:58:24.540
non-profit organizations
or corporations that

00:58:24.540 --> 00:58:33.730
have $100s of millions in
funding to do the moral thing,

00:58:33.730 --> 00:58:35.864
and meet their commitments?

00:58:35.864 --> 00:58:38.030
WAYNE PACELLE: Well, you
articulated that very well.

00:58:38.030 --> 00:58:39.366
Thank you for doing that.

00:58:39.366 --> 00:58:40.490
Thank you for following it.

00:58:40.490 --> 00:58:43.350
I mean, this is a case of
someone creating a problem,

00:58:43.350 --> 00:58:46.210
and passing the cost
on to someone else.

00:58:46.210 --> 00:58:47.900
So after the New
York Blood Center,

00:58:47.900 --> 00:58:51.740
which is a large charity-- a
public health-oriented charity

00:58:51.740 --> 00:58:55.280
that obviously does
blood-oriented work,

00:58:55.280 --> 00:58:58.670
important work-- they had
used chimps in research,

00:58:58.670 --> 00:59:02.230
stopped using them, had this
colony of them in Liberia,

00:59:02.230 --> 00:59:06.330
was supporting them to
maintain their health

00:59:06.330 --> 00:59:09.300
and well being, as they had
pledged to do a number of years

00:59:09.300 --> 00:59:10.280
ago.

00:59:10.280 --> 00:59:12.685
Again, if you use
a chimpanzee-- this

00:59:12.685 --> 00:59:15.190
is what happens in film
as well, or commercials.

00:59:15.190 --> 00:59:19.535
Here you see these cute infant
or juvenile chimpanzees.

00:59:19.535 --> 00:59:21.410
When they get to be
seven or eight years old,

00:59:21.410 --> 00:59:23.010
they become too
powerful to maintain.

00:59:23.010 --> 00:59:24.910
They can't be used on set.

00:59:24.910 --> 00:59:26.650
They live for 60 years,
so they dump them

00:59:26.650 --> 00:59:29.860
onto us and other animal welfare
groups and chimp protection

00:59:29.860 --> 00:59:30.360
groups.

00:59:30.360 --> 00:59:32.170
We have to care for
them another 50 years.

00:59:32.170 --> 00:59:35.760
We're talking about it
costs, on average, $17,000

00:59:35.760 --> 00:59:37.820
to care for a chimp every year.

00:59:37.820 --> 00:59:40.090
Look at that times 50 years.

00:59:40.090 --> 00:59:42.510
It's approaching
$1 million dollars.

00:59:42.510 --> 00:59:46.050
So where does
responsibility come in?

00:59:46.050 --> 00:59:48.240
That kind of goes
to your question.

00:59:48.240 --> 00:59:51.400
People create the problem, then
they dump it on the rest of us?

00:59:51.400 --> 00:59:55.220
We need a fuller accounting of
what's going on in our society.

00:59:55.220 --> 00:59:57.990
We need a fuller accounting
of factory farming.

00:59:57.990 --> 01:00:00.159
I mean, we think
of this cheap meat,

01:00:00.159 --> 01:00:01.700
where we have all
these public health

01:00:01.700 --> 01:00:04.260
costs that are transferred
to society in terms

01:00:04.260 --> 01:00:06.770
of heart disease and obesity.

01:00:06.770 --> 01:00:09.450
We have public health risks in
terms of antibiotic resistant

01:00:09.450 --> 01:00:12.434
bacteria, because we're dosing
these animals with antibiotics.

01:00:12.434 --> 01:00:14.850
They're dumping their manure
in our streams and our lakes,

01:00:14.850 --> 01:00:17.550
and they're poisoning
fish, and diminishing

01:00:17.550 --> 01:00:24.840
the recreational qualities of
these water areas-- on and on.

01:00:24.840 --> 01:00:26.920
So the New York Blood
Center as a charity

01:00:26.920 --> 01:00:29.220
just completely
dropped the ball.

01:00:29.220 --> 01:00:30.619
And we're picking up the slack.

01:00:30.619 --> 01:00:31.660
But we shouldn't have to.

01:00:31.660 --> 01:00:34.300
I'd say keep tabs
on our website.

01:00:34.300 --> 01:00:36.890
We're urging people to
write to the Blood Center,

01:00:36.890 --> 01:00:38.122
hold them accountable.

01:00:38.122 --> 01:00:39.830
And I can assure you
that we're not going

01:00:39.830 --> 01:00:41.760
to let them get away with it.

01:00:41.760 --> 01:00:44.260
We're going to
stick with the plan.

01:00:44.260 --> 01:00:45.450
Thank you.

01:00:45.450 --> 01:00:47.825
AUDIENCE: I had a question
about how you guys are working

01:00:47.825 --> 01:00:51.730
with veterinarians, specifically
for live animal veterinarians,

01:00:51.730 --> 01:00:54.430
and also food animal vets.

01:00:54.430 --> 01:00:56.620
WAYNE PACELLE: Well,
we have a division

01:00:56.620 --> 01:00:59.300
called the Humane Society
Veterinary Medical Association.

01:00:59.300 --> 01:01:03.120
So we have about 7,000 vets,
or about 70,000 to 80,000 vets

01:01:03.120 --> 01:01:04.252
in the US.

01:01:04.252 --> 01:01:05.710
Most of them are
small animal vets,

01:01:05.710 --> 01:01:07.450
but there are
categories of them.

01:01:07.450 --> 01:01:11.050
There are farm animal vets,
lab animal vets, equine vets.

01:01:11.050 --> 01:01:14.140
And we're trying to get
vets in a bigger leadership

01:01:14.140 --> 01:01:15.840
position in animal protection.

01:01:15.840 --> 01:01:18.900
Most vets historically worked
for the industries that

01:01:18.900 --> 01:01:20.250
were causing harm to animals.

01:01:20.250 --> 01:01:23.330
And they then internalized,
and then externalized

01:01:23.330 --> 01:01:24.870
their value system.

01:01:24.870 --> 01:01:26.600
And they were part
of the problem.

01:01:26.600 --> 01:01:33.960
Now, with women now dominating
veterinary school slots--

01:01:33.960 --> 01:01:37.030
it used to be 90/10 male
to female in vet schools.

01:01:37.030 --> 01:01:39.610
Now it's 90/10 females.

01:01:39.610 --> 01:01:42.459
And with small animal
vets caring for pets,

01:01:42.459 --> 01:01:44.000
not associated with
these industries,

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:46.461
there's a big revolution
happening in the vet field.

01:01:46.461 --> 01:01:47.460
We want to encourage it.

01:01:47.460 --> 01:01:49.709
And that's why we've got the
Humane Society Veterinary

01:01:49.709 --> 01:01:52.550
Medical Association working.

01:01:52.550 --> 01:01:54.080
So thank you all very much.

01:01:54.080 --> 01:01:55.130
Thanks for having me.

01:01:55.130 --> 01:01:58.490
Thanks, everyone, for taking
time from your work day.

01:01:58.490 --> 01:01:59.090
Thank you.

01:01:59.090 --> 01:02:00.640
[APPLAUSE]

